  <div class="morphology-header">
    <h1 class="morph-page-title">Morphology: The Analysis of Words</h1>
    <p class="morphology-lead">
      This page follows <strong>Chapter 4</strong> of Park-Johnson &amp; Shin’s <em>Linguistics for Language Teachers</em>:
      morphemes, how words are built, and why that matters for classrooms. Below is a concise tour of the chapter; the 3D
      “garden” lets you <strong>see</strong> shared affixes across English words. Drag to orbit, scroll or pinch to zoom,
      and use <strong>Explore</strong> to fly the camera to a tree. American English examples only.
    </p>
    <p class="morphology-cite">
      <strong>Source:</strong> Park-Johnson, S., &amp; Shin, S. J. (2020). <em>Linguistics for Language Teachers</em>.
      Taylor &amp; Francis. Section labels (§4.2–§4.7) match the chapter outline you are using in class.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="morph-reading" aria-labelledby="morph-overview">
    <h2 id="morph-overview" class="morph-h2">Ideas from Chapter 4</h2>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.2</span> Morphemes</h3>
    <p>
      A <strong>morpheme</strong> is the smallest linguistic unit that carries meaning or a grammatical function. Words
      like <em>teacher</em> illustrate the point: <em>teach</em> is one morpheme (the content of “give instruction”),
      and <strong>-er</strong> is another (roughly “one who,” and it turns the chunk into a noun). By contrast,
      <em>happy</em> is a <strong>simple word</strong>—one morpheme, even though it has two syllables. <em>Impersonal</em>
      is <strong>complex</strong>: three morphemes (<strong>im-</strong>, <strong>person</strong>, <strong>-al</strong>
      in the book’s segmentation). The chapter’s mantra: <strong>do not confuse morphemes with syllables</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Complex words usually contain a <strong>root</strong> (the core meaning; often a noun, verb, adjective, or
      preposition in English) plus <strong>affixes</strong>. An affix before the root is a <strong>prefix</strong>
      (<em>dis-</em> in <em>dishonest</em>); after the root, a <strong>suffix</strong> (<em>-ful</em> in
      <em>beautiful</em>). Some languages also use <strong>infixes</strong> (inserted inside a root) and
      <strong>circumfixes</strong> (discontinuous pieces around a root); the textbook illustrates these with Indonesian
      and Malay so students see English is not the whole story.
    </p>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.3</span> Classifying morphemes</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Free morphemes</strong> can stand alone; <strong>bound morphemes</strong> must attach to something else.
      Most English roots are free, but the book also cites bound roots such as <em>ept</em> in <em>inept</em> and
      <em>mit</em> in <em>remit</em>. Free morphemes split into <strong>content morphemes</strong> (open-class items:
      nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs) and <strong>function morphemes</strong> (closed-class items: articles,
      conjunctions, prepositions, pronouns). Bound morphemes include bound roots, <strong>derivational affixes</strong>,
      and <strong>inflectional affixes</strong>.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrapper morph-table-wide">
      <table>
        <caption>
          Table 4.1 in brief — free vs. bound, content vs. function (Park-Johnson &amp; Shin)
        </caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col"></th>
            <th scope="col">Content orientation</th>
            <th scope="col">Grammar orientation</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Free morphemes</th>
            <td><strong>Open class</strong> — nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs (e.g. <em>cat</em>, <em>go</em>, <em>happy</em>)</td>
            <td><strong>Closed class</strong> — articles, conjunctions, prepositions, pronouns (e.g. <em>the</em>, <em>and</em>, <em>in</em>)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Bound morphemes</th>
            <td>Bound roots (<em>ept</em>, <em>mit</em>) + <strong>derivational affixes</strong> (e.g. <em>re-</em>, <em>un-</em>, <em>-ness</em>, <em>-ize</em>)</td>
            <td><strong>Inflectional suffixes</strong> only in English — plural <em>-s</em>, possessive <em>’s</em>, verbal <em>-s / -ing / -ed</em>, comparative <em>-er</em>, superlative <em>-est</em></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="morph-pair-head"><strong>Derivational morphemes</strong> (from the chapter’s summary):</p>
    <ul class="morph-list">
      <li>May change part of speech and/or meaning (e.g. <em>-ment</em> in <em>statement</em>; <em>re-</em> in <em>rewrite</em>).</li>
      <li>Are <strong>not required by syntax</strong> — removing <em>un-</em> from <em>unhappy</em> still leaves a grammatical sentence, just a different meaning.</li>
      <li>Are <strong>selective</strong> about what they combine with (the book’s <sup>*</sup><em>friendhood</em> example).</li>
      <li>Usually attach <strong>before</strong> inflectional suffixes (e.g. <em>state-ment-s</em>).</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="morph-pair-head"><strong>Inflectional morphemes</strong> in English (eight suffixes; Table 4.3):</p>
    <ul class="morph-list">
      <li>Do <strong>not</strong> change the basic part of speech or lexical meaning (<em>big</em> → <em>bigger</em>).</li>
      <li>Are often <strong>required by syntax</strong> (e.g. third-person <em>-s</em>: <em>The boy likes to read</em>).</li>
      <li>Apply across large classes of words (regular plural <em>-s</em>).</li>
      <li>Appear at the <strong>outer edge</strong> of the word.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="morph-callout">
      <strong>Sample affix meanings (Table 4.2).</strong> The chapter lists glosses such as
      <em>un-</em> “not / opposite of,” <em>-able / -ible</em> “capable of being,” <em>-al</em> “pertaining to,”
      <em>-ment</em> “condition of,” <em>-ize</em> “become,” <em>-ness</em> “state of being,” and several more. The 3D
      garden reuses many of these pieces so you can recognize them in new vocabulary.
    </div>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.4</span> Allomorphs</h3>
    <p>
      Just as allophones are surface forms of a phoneme, <strong>allomorphs</strong> are predictable variants of a
      morpheme. The plural morpheme spelled <em>-s</em> is pronounced [s], [z], or [ɪz] depending on the final sound of
      the noun; past-tense <em>-ed</em> has [t], [d], and [ɪd]. The indefinite article alternates between
      <em>a</em> and <em>an</em> for phonological reasons. The interactive trees here use spelling; your class can map
      the same morphemes to their spoken allomorphs.
    </p>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.5</span> Inflection</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Inflection</strong> adjusts a word’s form for grammar (number, tense, possession, comparison). The
      textbook contrasts richly inflecting languages with English, which has relatively little inflection and therefore
      relies more on word order and function words. That cross-linguistic lens is part of why morphology matters for
      teachers working with multilingual learners.
    </p>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.6</span> Other morphological processes</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Compounding</strong> combines whole words. In English, the <strong>right-hand member</strong> often
      determines the word class (<em>whiteboard</em> is a noun like <em>board</em>). Spelling varies: solid
      (<em>backbone</em>), hyphenated (<em>sugar-free</em>), or open (<em>school bus</em>)—still one compound
      morphologically. The chapter also surveys <strong>reduplication</strong>, <strong>internal modification</strong>
      (e.g. irregular <em>man / men</em>), <strong>stress shifts</strong> (<em>réfund / refúnd</em>), and
      <strong>suppletion</strong> (<em>go / went</em>; pronoun case paradigms).
    </p>

    <h3 class="morph-h3"><span class="morph-sec">§4.7</span> Teaching word formation</h3>
    <p>
      The closing section ties morphology to <strong>vocabulary instruction</strong>: cognates, word families, and
      small differences among related forms (the book uses <em>nutrient</em> vs. <em>nutrition</em>). Morphological
      awareness helps learners guess and remember academic words—especially when teachers make affix meanings explicit.
    </p>

    <h3 class="morph-h3">Using the garden below</h3>
    <p>
      Magenta lines link the <strong>same bound morpheme</strong> across different words (for example
      <strong>de-</strong>, <strong>re-</strong>, <strong>-ation</strong>, <strong>-able</strong>). Two trees for
      <em>unlockable</em> show <strong>structural ambiguity</strong>: identical spelling, different bracketing, different
      meanings—made concrete in the sample sentences attached to each tree.
    </p>
